        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-07-29T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-07-29T19:00:00-05:00" n="103"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d103">
                <head>103. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Iran<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d103fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 84, Tehran Embassy Files, 1950–1952,
                        classified general records, Box 25. Secret; Security Information; Priority.
                        Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_SJHJ_1">Stutesman</persName>; cleared in
                            <gloss target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss> by <persName corresp="#p_JJD_1"
                            >Jernegan</persName>, in <gloss target="#t_SP_1">S/P</gloss> by
                            <persName corresp="#p_NPH_1">Nitze</persName>; and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MHF_1">Matthews</persName>. Repeated to London.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1952-07-29T20:00:00-04:00">July 29, 1952, 8 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>255. <gloss target="#t_Brit_1">Brit</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb_1">Emb</gloss> reps called this morning to discuss
                    complicated and ominous Iran situation. We here do not see the possibility at
                    this time of a more constructive alternative to <persName corresp="#p_MM_1"
                        >Mosadeq</persName> for the reasons outlined in our 585 July 26.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d103fn2">
                        <ref target="#d99">Document 99</ref>.</note> However, in view of <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName>’s attitude as expressed in your 423
                    July 28 we believe that every possibility should be reexplored.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d103fn3">Presumably a reference to telegram 422 from Tehran, July
                        28; see <ref target="#d100">Document 100</ref>.</note> It was therefore
                    agreed request <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_Brit_1"
                        >Brit</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb_1">Emb</gloss> in Tehran make joint reappraisal situation
                    to include (A) recommendations as to possible joint courses action by <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss>; (B) possible
                    alternatives to <persName corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> (C) methods bring
                    such alternative to power; (D) form encouragement and support which would be
                    necessary.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI_1">FYI</gloss> Brits expressed grave concern re
                    developments Iran and stated primary objective now is to save Iran from
                    communism. However, at same time impression gained that Brits not yet willing
                    capitulate entirely to Irans in oil dispute even though this position might mean
                    loss Iran to West.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_ADG_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG_1">Acheson</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
